  "prompt": "What are the merits and demerits of collegium system for appointment of supreme Court judges?",
  "response": "Merits of the Collegium System:\n\n1. Judicial Independence\n- Prevents direct government interference in judiciary appointments\n- Helps maintain separation of powers\n- Reduces political manipulation in judicial selection\n\n2. Expertise-based Selection\n- Judges select judges based on professional competence\n- Deeper understanding of judicial requirements\n- Considers merit, experience, and integrity\n\n3. Collegiate Decision-making\n- Multiple judges participate in selection process\n- Reduces individual bias\n- Ensures comprehensive evaluation of candidates\n\n4. Transparency in Consultation\n- Collective consultation among senior judges\n- Reduces chances of arbitrary selection\n- Promotes collective wisdom\n\nDemerits of the Collegium System:\n\n1. Lack of Accountability\n- No external oversight mechanism\n- Limited transparency in selection process\n- Minimal constitutional checks and balances\n\n2. Potential Nepotism\n- Possibility of subjective selections\n- Closed-loop system favoring known candidates\n- Limited representation of diverse backgrounds\n\n3. Absence of Clear Selection Criteria\n- No standardized, objective selection parameters\n- Discretionary powers of existing judges\n- Potential for inconsistent appointments\n\n4. Limited Public Representation\n- No direct public or parliamentary involvement\n- Closed judicial club-like mechanism\n- Reduced democratic accountability\n\n5. Potential Self-perpetuation\n- Judges selecting future judges\n- Risk of maintaining status quo\n- Limited scope for external perspectives\n\nThese aspects highlight the complex nature of the collegium system, balancing judicial independence with potential systemic limitations.",
